item.title: Education
item.dc:creator: Shin
item.content:encoded:
Additive Manufacturing (AM)

Video credit: University of Sheffield

A process of joining materials to make objects from 3D model data, usually layer upon layer, as opposed to subtractive methodologies.

 

3D Printing

Video credit: Global Television 16x9

A term often used synonymously with additive manufacturing; in particular associated with low end or the consumer industry.

item.title: Airbus, NPU of China cooperate in 3D printing research
item.dc:creator: Shin Huang
item.content:encoded:
Image credit: Airbus

Airbus and North Western Polytechnical University (NPU) of China have signed an R&D agreement to jointly develop additive manufacturing applications for the aviation industry.

Image credit: Bright Laser Technologies

Under this agreement, titanium alloy specimens will be manufactured by Bright Laser Technologies, a spin-off of NPU using Laser Solid Forming (LSF) - a metal deposition based additive manufacturing technology developed by NPU's State Key Laboratory of Solidification Processing (SKLSP) since 1995. Source: Airbus, Bright Laser Technologies

item.title: Events & Activities

Society Launch Event!

Our first event is on Thursday week 3 (May 15) at 6pm. Join us at the Oxford Launchpad, Said Business School if you are curious about 3D printing or interested in getting involved with the society or just want to have some fun socialising. It will be held together with Renegades' Mix at Six as part of Digital Oxford Week 2014.  Special guests:
  • Hagan Bayley - Professor of Chemical Biology
  • Stuart Jackson - Head of EOS UK
  • Jeremy Pullin - Head of Rapid Manufacturing, Renishaw
Wine and refreshments will be served.

item.title: $50 3D-printed hand vs. $42,000 prosthetic arm
item.dc:creator: Shin Huang
item.content:encoded:
Image credit: e-NABLE

Jose Delgado Jr. recently replaced his myoelectric prosthetic arm that cost $42,000 with a 3D printed e-NABLE Hand at $50, also called Cyborg Beast. It is made of ABS plastic and is completely a mechanical design, created as a collaboration between Jorge Zuniga, Ivan Owen and Peter Binkley, all part of the growing e-NABLE community whose 650 volunteers are working on providing cheap assistive devices to the world.

Video credit: 3Duniverse

In an interview with Jeremy Simon, founder of 3Duniverse and an e-NABLE member, Jose says that the grip is stronger which is particular important for daily tasks such as box lifting and driving. Source: 3Duniverse

item.title: UK to invest £14.7 million in 3D printing projects
item.dc:creator: Shin Huang
item.content:encoded:
Image credit: GOV.UK

UK business secretary Vince Cable announced a plan to invest £14.7 million in 3D printing R&D projects, part of a wider move by the government to boost the domestic manufacturing industries. The investment will help businesses to develop innovative manufacturing solutions in 3D printing technologies that are otherwise too risky or capital-intensive to be developed on their own. Examples such as the  facial implant project by Renishaw;  the hip replacement project by JRI Orthopaedics and customised medical insoles by FDM Digital Solutions. The projects will last between one and three years. The Technology Strategy Board and Research Councils will contribute £8.4 million to the programme and set to raise £6.3 million via private placements. Source: GOV.UK

item.title: Melting-based Process
item.dc:creator: Shin
item.content:encoded:
Selective Laser Melting (SLM)

Synonyms: Direct Metal Laser Sintering (DMLS) Video credit: GPIprototype

The process starts by numerically slicing a 3D CAD model into a number of finite layers. For each sliced layer a laser scan path is calculated which defines both the boundary contour and some form of fill sequence, often a raster pattern. Each layer is then sequentially recreated by depositing metal powder layers, one on top of the other, and melting their surface by scanning a laser beam.

The metal powder is spread uniformly by a wiper. A laser fully melts the pre-deposited powder layer. The melted particles fuse and solidify to form a layer of the component. 

 

Electron Beam Melting (EBM)

Video credit: Oak Ridge National Laboratory

A similar process to SLM, the main difference being that EBM uses an electron beam as its power source.

item.title: Sintering-based Process
item.dc:creator: Shin
item.content:encoded:
Selective Laser Sintering (SLS)

Video credit: 3D Systems

The process starts by numerically slicing a 3D CAD model into a number of finite layers. For each sliced layer a laser scan path is calculated  which defines both the boundary contour and some form of fill sequence, often a raster pattern. Each layer is then sequentially recreated by depositing powder layers, one on top of the other, and sintering their surface by scanning a laser beam.

The powder is spread uniformly by a wiper. A laser fully sinters the pre-deposited powder layer. The sintered materials then form a layer of the component.

item.title: Deposition-based Process
item.dc:creator: Shin
item.content:encoded:
Laser Metal Deposition (LMD)

Synonyms: Direct Laser Deposition (DLD), Direct Metal Deposition (DMD), Laser Cladding, Laser Engineered Net Shaping (LENS), Laser Solid Forming (LSF), etc.

Video credit: Trumpf

A welding-based process which uses a laser beam to form a melt pool on a metallic substrate, into which metal powder is fed. The powder melts to form a deposit that is fusion bonded to the substrate. The required geometry is built up layer by layer. Both the laser and nozzle from which the powder is delivered are manipulated using a gantry system or robotic arm.

item.title: Google Project Ara - affordable, Lego, smartphone
item.dc:creator: Shin Huang
item.content:encoded:
Image credit: Project Ara

Google's R&D Project Ara is aiming to develop an affordable and highly-customisable phone that will allow users to design and make personal choices of their device's hardware via an open platform. The finished products are likely to be a cross between a Mondrian painting and Lego. The first Modular Developers Kit (MDK) is available on the project's website.

Video credit: Phonebloks

3D Systems is an collaborator on the project. It is also developing a high-speed continuous 3D printing system that is capable of mass producing customised Ara modules. This system will incorporate multi-material printing, such as conductive inks and antennas, and subtractive machining processes. Source: Project Ara, 3D Systems

item.content:encoded:
Membership

Membership gives you free entry to our workshops and speaker events, discount or free for your designed 3D printing, half price entry to our socials and the opportunity to have dinner with our speakers.
  • Oxford or Brookes: £10 (1 year) or £20 (life)
  • Non-Oxford students: £12 (1 year) or £22 (life)
  • Others: £15 (1 year) or £25 (life)

item.title: Workshops
item.dc:creator: Shin
item.content:encoded:
Workshop I - CAD Design for 3D Printing

Our first workshop will be held on Oct. 18th, 2014 at the Oxford Launchpad, Said Business School as part of the Women Impact on Engineering, Technology and Enterprise Conference (TICKETS).

Whether you are an artist or an amateur design hobbyist, this workshop aims to help you become comfortable using simple 3D CAD design software for 3D printing. You will have the chance to design your own personal models. A selection of top designs will be printed for free.

Instructor Speaker| Paul Doyle

Paul Doyle is the head of Access, Research and Development at Hereward College. He has been engaged in the field of Assistive Technology since 1995 in a variety of operational and strategic roles.

Paul leads a team of researchers undertaking projects in and around the field of AT, with objectives as diverse as capturing the user experience of innovations in AT to workforce development requirements projects for the assessment and installation of telehealth and telecare assistive technologies.

TICKETS

item.title: SpaceX's Dragon V2 to use 3D-printed rocket engine
item.dc:creator: Shin Huang
item.content:encoded:
Image credit: SpaceX

SpaceX CEO Elon Musk unveiled the company's next generation spacecraft Dragon V2 - the world's first reusable spacecraft capable of power landing with pinpoint accuracy.

Video credit: SpaceX

Its SuperDraco rocket engine can produce up to 73,000 newtons of thrust, 180 times more powerful than the previous Draco engine used on Dragon V1 - the first private spacecraft to the International Space Station. The engine's combustion chamber will be 3D printed of inconel - a nickel-based superalloy using SLM or DMLS technology. This will make SuperDraco the world's first commercially 3D printed rocket engine.

Image credit: SpaceX

Source: SpaceX

item.title: Assistive technology - 'Andiamo' and 'Enabling the future'
item.dc:creator: Mark
item.content:encoded: Medical researchers at "Enabling the Future" were able to create a hand prosthesis using 3D printing, which is faster and more affordable than existing techniques. In London, 'Andiamo' are creating a service for disabled children using 3D scanners and replacement prosthesis.  The designs for the open source Ody Hand are available here. Andiamo - The current completion in the area of adaptive technology needs some serious competition. Basically the latest manufacturer of human support braces in orthotics was founded 30 years ago. The materials used are formed from wood and steel and take on average 28 weeks to manufacture.  In many cases this is too long for the devices to be useful for the children, since they are growing quickly. Andiamo can reduce the time for manufacturing to circa one week or less, which allows the device to serve the function immediately.  Naveed Parvez also said the devices are manufactured using digits to wigits based in London.  The 3D scanner is based in Kingtson university and costs around £20,000. Lower quality scanners are available such as the Xbox scanner which is under £500. The 3D scan and 3D print is significantly better than the existing wood and steel solution because it is made to measure and the results have less variation. The speed and technology make the results more dependable and consistent than the other products which are from the 1980s.
